::[https://theconversation.com/iran-protests-2026-our-surveys-show-iranians-agree-more-on-regime-change-than-what-might-come-next-273198 Maleki + Arab, 12 Jan 2026], in ''[[The Conversation]]'', argue that the Iranian protests are primarily from internal popular opposition to the current system of government in Iran, presenting [https://gamaan.org GAMAAN] statistics of public opinion through to Sep 2025 (no more recent survey, apparently), plus their interpretations through to 12 Jan 2026. They do make some links with the chain of causal factors defined per this article by starting at the 7 October 2023 attacks, via the 12-day war: {{tq|We believe we are currently witnessing another spike, given the increase observed after the 12-day war. [graph] In contrast with the context of previous protests, the regime is militarily weakened from the 12-day war, ...}} They're not claiming that the 12-day war was the main causal factor, but they do seem to attribute it as ''one of'' many contributing factors. Most sociopolitical events have many contributing factors.{{pb}}The [[climate crisis|climate emergency]] is a likely causal factor too, via the [[Tehran water shortage]], since it's hard to believe that people would not be furious about nearly having to evacuate the city; however, someone would have to find a [[WP:RS]] to support that as a contributing factor.{{pb}}There could be some good sources found by looking through the [[reactions to the 2025–2026 Iranian protests]] article, as well as stuff that ''should have gone'' in the sub-article but instead got crammed into [[2025–2026 Iranian protests#Reactions]]. [[User:Boud|Boud]] ([[User talk:Boud|talk]]) 15:59, 18 February 2026 (UTC)
